english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Collection of National Teacher Jeongmyeong of Baekryeon Monastery on Mount Mandeok
  author: Im Gyeae-il
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The composition of literature is truly a minor pursuit of the Buddhist path. Yet from the Tang and Song dynasties onward, the poetry collections of more than forty eminent monks have circulated in the world—and this too is worthy of admiration. Though some, insufficiently trained in the Buddha's way, have merely sheltered themselves in the stream of letters to indulge in idle fancy, those who have harmonized both Confucian and Buddhist learning and attained the lofty purity of spiritual conduct are rarely heard of in antiquity.

    The National Teacher, whose name was Cheonin, came from the Park clan and was a native of Yeonsan. From his youth, he was brilliant and acute, widely learned with a prodigious memory, and renowned for his literary skill. He was recommended as a scholar and entered the examination halls with the expectation of immediate success, yet throughout his life he failed to advance through the spring examinations. The literati all lamented this misfortune. He then renounced the world and departed with his dormitory companion Heo Jeok, the former scholar-official Shin Geuk-jeong, their robes cast aside for a distant path. They arrived at Mount Mandeok and paid reverence to National Teacher Wonmyo. After the bonds of cultivation fell away, he sought out Snim on Mount Songgwang and grasped the essence of the Caoxi teaching, returning to his old mountain. He submitted to his master's guidance, recited the Lotus Sutra, and opened the Bodhisattva Samantabhadra's meditation hall. After two years, he returned to live in solitude on Mount Jiri. Later he moved his staff to Mount Biseul, concealing his traces while cultivating the true way for many years before returning.

    When National Teacher Wonmyo, now aged, transmitted the Tendai teaching and doctrine, his wisdom and understanding fully matured, and his eloquent debate arose like wind. When the National Teacher wished to pass the seat to him, the Snim withdrew himself and fled to Mount Gongdeok in the Upper Falls. At that time, the present Prime Minister Choi Ja, who served as governor, established the Rice-and-Flour Society to invite him. The Snim intended to grow old there, but the National Teacher sent people again, forcing and reproaching him, saying, "How can you abandon us so carelessly?" Unable to refuse, he returned to oversee the monastery gate—such was the will of the congregation.

    In the winter of the Jeongmi year, fleeing from bandits, he entered the Law Flower Monastery on Mount Sangwang. Though he fell ill with a minor ailment, the king sent a messenger bearing a letter and medicinal provisions. In the seventh month of the following year, he transmitted the dharma to his disciple Won-wan and entrusted him, saying: "When I have passed, do not arrange elaborate funerals or erect stupas, do not seek out the powerful for memorial inscriptions, but simply cremate my body in some abandoned place." That day he withdrew to Yongheul Hermitage south of the mountain, closed his gate, severed his worldly affairs, and lived in perfect stillness.

    On the fourth day of the eighth month, he called his disciples and said, "I am departing now." He wrote letters to Prime Minister Choi and Minister Jeong, and to his dharma-brother Cheongil. On the fifth day, after bathing and changing his robes, he ascended the seat and spoke with measured voice: "Where shall the great man's soaring spirit-flame be put to use?" When an attendant asked where the four lands' pure realm appeared before him, which realm he would enter, he answered: "The realm of singular nature alone." Then addressing the assembly, he said: "This ailing monk has eaten nothing for more than ten days, and my legs grow terribly weak. Yet receiving the secret support of the dharma-body, my strength returns. With these legs I could go to heaven, or to any Buddha-realm. The five aggregates are utterly purified, the three worlds leave not a trace." He then spoke a verse:

    "The half-moon glows bright through white clouds of autumn,
    The wind carries the spring's voice—but where does it go?
    The boundless Buddha-realms of all ten directions
    Accomplish the Buddha's work through the endless future."

    When he finished speaking, he passed away. He was forty-four years old; his monastic age was twenty-three. His disciple Jeonggwan dreamed he traveled to some place where a voice cried out: "The Venerable Yin has already attained the superior rebirth!" Many other miraculous signs are recorded in his spiritual biography, which I omit here.

    From the time of his ordination, the Snim did not favor writing. Though his exchanges with others produced considerable poetry and prose, he did not permit his disciples to compile his works, so eight or nine out of ten pieces were lost. Yet I have gathered many remnants from his later years and divided them into three volumes. I was fortunate to bear the name of the Fragrant Society in close association with him, which explains this task. After the Snim's passing, national affairs multiplied and no stone monument could be erected to praise his virtue—though this too was his own wish. I feared only that his traces might be lost to obscurity and later generations left without record. When a fellow traveler of the way brought me his biography and poetry collection, I dared not excuse myself with claims of inadequacy. I have here briefly sketched the Snim's legacy—yet this is merely offering a grain of sand from Mount Tai.
  footnotes:
    - The 'spring examinations' (춘관) refer to the civil service examinations conducted in spring, the primary pathway to official advancement in the Joseon period.
    - Mount Mandeok (萬德山) and Baekryeon Monastery (白蓮社) were important Buddhist centers in medieval Korea.
    - The reference to the 'four lands' pure realm' alludes to the Buddhist cosmology of the four celestial realms and their corresponding pure Buddha-lands.
    - The 'superior rebirth' (상품 하세) refers to the highest grade of rebirth in Sukhavati (the Pure Land), the ultimate aspiration in Pure Land Buddhism.
